.SS "defineTileSet (int tileWidth, int tileHeight, \fBImage\fP tiles, boolean hasTransparency = \fRtrue\fP, boolean flipTiles = \fRfalse\fP)"

.PP
define image and dimensions for the tiles used by this layer Each \fBTileLayer\fP has a set of equal size tiles taken from a single image\&. The tileWidth and tileHeight specify the size of each individual tile in the image, and the image should divide evenly into tiles with no left-over space\&. There can be at most 256 tiles in an image\&.

.PP
Tile sets can contain transparency, either through a transparent color or via an alpha channel (See \fBImage\fP for more details on transparency)\&.

.PP
Tile sets can support tile rotation (facing) or tile flipping (vertical, horizontal, or both)\&. You cannot use both rotation and flipping in the same layer\&.

.PP
To support rotation, you must have a maximum of 64 tiles in your tile set\&. Typically the tiles would be arranged in an 8x8 grid, with the top left corner tile being considered tile 0 and then counting left to right, top to bottom\&.

.PP
To support flipping in both directions, your tile set should be laid out just like for rotation, 64 tiles in an 8x8 grid\&. For horizontal flipping only, you should have 128 tiles in an 8x16 grid, and for vertical flipping only you should have 128 tile in a 16x8 grid\&. For all kinds of flipping you must pass true for the flipTiles parameter when you call \fBdefineTileSet()\fP\&. 
.SS "\fBMemBlock\fP getMapData (int mapWidth = \fR0\fP, int mapHeight = \fR0\fP, int srcX, int srcY)"

.PP
Extract a rectangular region of tile data from the layer\&. This function extracts a rectangular region of tile data from the \fBTileLayer\fP and returns it as a BinaryString containing the tile indices\&.

.PP
\fBParameters\fP
.RS 4
\fImapWidth\fP The width of the region to extract (number of tiles horizontally) 
.br
\fImapHeight\fP The height of the region to extract (number of tiles vertically) 
.br
\fIsrcX\fP The X coordinate of the top-left corner of the region to extract 
.br
\fIsrcY\fP The Y coordinate of the top-left corner of the region to extract
.RE
.PP
The function returns a BinaryString containing tile indices arranged in row-major order (left to right, top to bottom)\&. Each byte in the returned data represents a tile index from the specified region\&.

.PP
The extracted data can be used with \fBTileLayer::loadMapData()\fP to copy tile data between layers or save it for later use\&.

.PP
\fBReturns\fP
.RS 4
A BinaryString containing the tile indices from the specified region
.RE
.PP
\fBWarning\fP
.RS 4
If the requested region extends beyond the layer boundaries, the behavior is undefined 
.RE
.PP
\fBNote\fP
.RS 4
The returned data format is compatible with \fBTileLayer::loadMapData(BinaryString, int, int, int, int)\fP
.RE
.PP
\fBSee also\fP
.RS 4
\fBTileLayer::loadMapData(BinaryString, int, int, int, int)\fP 

.PP
\fBTileLayer::loadMapData(MemBlock, int, int, int, int)\fP 

.PP
BinaryString 
.RE
.PP

